  <span id="freeText7957492698986091636" style="display:none">Ross Douthat, columnist, <i>New York Times</i>: "Wars fought on behalf of Christianity can only be justified as unfortunate necessities."<br /><br />Raoul de Caen, Frankish historian, present in the Middle East at the turn of the 11th and 12th centuries, writing about the European crusaders in his <i>Gesta Tancredi</i>: "In Ma'arra [in northwest Syria] our troops boiled pagan adults in cooking-pots; they impaled children on spits and devoured them grilled."<br /><br />A quick way to feel despair is to imagine these two quotes circling and chasing each other forever, like a double helix, and never touching.</span>
