<div id="review_1757141984" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1757141984" />
    <a title="Greet" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59610999-greet"><img alt="Greet" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1757141984?book_show_action=true">Sep 13, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greet" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greet" href="/user/show/59610999-greet">Greet</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780805208986" href="/book/show/64533.The_Crusades_Through_Arab_Eyes">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1757141984" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer225841650521803531">With all respect for Malouf, but this book lacks a great deal of objectivity. I have to meet the first person involved in a serious conflict, who will say something positive about his adversary. <br/>1) the crusades were a legitimate attempt of christian armies to stop the very bloody and cruel islam imperialism on christian soil and to gain back their holy places (I really wonder how muslims would react if we attacked and occupied Mecca, for that matter). A few quotes with regard to the islamic conq</span>
  <span id="freeText225841650521803531" style="display:none">With all respect for Malouf, but this book lacks a great deal of objectivity. I have to meet the first person involved in a serious conflict, who will say something positive about his adversary. <br />1) the crusades were a legitimate attempt of christian armies to stop the very bloody and cruel islam imperialism on christian soil and to gain back their holy places (I really wonder how muslims would react if we attacked and occupied Mecca, for that matter). A few quotes with regard to the islamic conquest: 'At Thessalonica in 903/4, 22000 Christians were enslaved. An eyewitness account notes: ‘the Saracens were unleashed like wild beasts’, ...’no mercy’...’no-one was spared’..’.all were pierced by the sword’..and the 300 hundred hiding in the church ..’the entire floor was covered with bodies, with a lake of blood in the middle’ (Bostom p 604).<br />'In 705 ‘Arabs penetrated Armenia, where they captured all the magnates and leaders of the people, brought them together, and burned them alive’ (Costantelos Bostom p 391).<br />Or what to say about the blood thirsty letter the Ottoman sultan sent to the people of Vienna (1683) <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.topix.com/forum/world/serbia/TANMM5ERVUMNN93LM">http://www.topix.com/forum/world/serb...</a><br />2) cannibalism of the crusaders was caused by famine, since muslims applied the scorched soil tactic, and there was no food to be found<br />3) there were cruelties and massacres on both sides and Saladin wasn't a saint neither. 200 of the Templar and Hospitaller Knights were taken prisoner (1183). Imad ed-Din, his secretary, wrote: <br />"Saladin ordered that they should be beheaded, choosing to have them dead rather than in prison. With him was a whole band of scholars and sufis and a certain number of devout men and ascetics, each begged to be allowed to kill one of them, and drew his sword and rolled back his sleeve. Saladin, his face joyful, was sitting on his dais, the unbelievers showed black despair." Saladin personally beheaded Raynald, a 60yo ally of King Guy<br />4) as for the cultural dominance of the Arabs: throughout Islam’s history to the present they have destroyed the books, libraries, art, and architecture of others because Islam regards all else as ‘ignorance.’Manuscripts from Greece, India, Egypt etc were translated into Arabic often by Christians.but the originals of particularly Greek and Latin texts were destroyed to preserve the illusion of Islamic superiority (Khan p 178). In Spain popular works of medicine, agriculture, astrology and geography were translated from Latin into Arabic generally by Arabised Christian slaves (Mozarabs) or dhimmis and many texts must have been derived from the Etymologies of Isidore of Seville and other Christian writers (Encyclopaedia Britannica Vol 17 p 419)<br />The appropriation of the work of others is typical for islam and has a long history but the truth appears when the Muslims are expelled from Europe, Europe progresses and the Islamic world sinks back to the barbarity of Islam. Are we to believe the Muslims gave great knowledge to us and just forgot it all themselves ? NO, it was not part of Islamic culture to begin with! All a Muslim needs to know is in the Koran and they are encouraged to seek religious knowledge, not follow unfettered intellectual inquiry (Warraq p 273). Mohammad taught blind adherence to Islam, not critical analysis or science and raged against poets, musicians and artists! Even Mohammad’s illiteracy is praised. Whatever was produced under Islamic domination came in spite of Islam not because of it and on closer inspection was appropriated from other conquered societies (Hindu, Greek, Christian, Jewish, Persian, Chinese), or carried out by non-Muslims including slaves and dhimmis (eg Avicebron, Isaac Israeli, Maimonides, Christian Bishop Barhebraeus) or those forced to ‘convert’ or indeed by some ‘Muslims’ who faced persecution for their un-Islamic ideas (Warraq p 272-275).<br />I think that the typical reactions on this book say it all. Westerners say mea culpa ant try to paint themselves even worse than they actually were, easterners play the victim card and rejoice in an imaginary heroic past. It is a synthesis of all that is wrong in the world today<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="225841650521803531" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
