        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3300520629" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3909924195974769414">Maalouf managed to put together the many resources from historians, poets, politicians and military advisors who lived through the Crusades, in a very talented image of detail capturing, in 350 pages, two of the longest and hardest centuries in Islamic history.<br/>He finishes his research with an amazing epilogue about the effect of the Crusades on the Arab world today and how it shapes their relationship with the outside world, and how, after a great phase of Arabs thriving in many aspects such as </span>
  <span id="freeText3909924195974769414" style="display:none">Maalouf managed to put together the many resources from historians, poets, politicians and military advisors who lived through the Crusades, in a very talented image of detail capturing, in 350 pages, two of the longest and hardest centuries in Islamic history.<br />He finishes his research with an amazing epilogue about the effect of the Crusades on the Arab world today and how it shapes their relationship with the outside world, and how, after a great phase of Arabs thriving in many aspects such as military arts, philosphy, science, literature, and the amazing life skills mentioned in the book, they preceded the Europeans, and after centuries of isolation and repititive attacks on them, closed themselves up against the whole world and never allowed other cultures be welcomed.<br /><br />Which is what we see in nowadays Arabian 'third world' countries.<br />Such a sad reality we live in, given how great our people were.<br /><br /><br />*****<br /><br />* on a side note:<br /><br /><b> [ ] ❛ In 1174, at the young age of 13, Baldwin IV successfully attacked Damascus in order to draw the Muslim Sultan Saladin away from Aleppo. In 1176 he was leading men from the front in similar attacks at Damascus and Andujar to repel Muslim attacks.[6] Baldwin also planned an attack on Saladin's power-base in Egypt. ❜<br /><br />❛ In November, Baldwin and Raynald of Châtillon defeated Saladin with the help of the Knights Templar at the celebrated Battle of Montgisard. ❜<br /><br />❛ Though often suffering from the effects of leprosy and ruling with regency governments, Baldwin was able to maintain himself as king for much longer than otherwise might have been expected. ❜<br /><br /></b> —; from Wikipedia.<br /><br />Maalouf didn't mention any activities by the Leper King, Baldwin IV, whose illness prevented him from living further than the age of 24.<br /><br /><br /><br />** also, just some empty thoughts.<br /><br />♧ So after I've finished The Crusades viewed by Arabs, I wanted to start the famous Assassin's Creed original novel series, but come to think about it—the former is historical non-fiction, and the latter is just.. a work of fiction and fantasy, mainly focused on romanticizing the frightening truth of the <b>
  <i>order of the Hashashins</i>
</b>, or in other words, the Islamic Shi'a. Here we have the fearful Hassan Al-Sabbagh, and there, the cool Ezio. So I decided to give up the idea, wanting the real facts to sink in.<br /><br />(I think Maalouf mentioned that when the Moguls, came they destroyed the scripts and books that could by today give us a more certain idea about the order. Besides, he explains this complicated history in a very simple way. What a great writer!)<br /><br /><br />♧♧ and lastly, don't you think if all kings and leaders thought like <i>Emperor Frederick II of Hohenstaufen</i>, how great the world would have been?<br /><br />♧♧♧ allow me to thank Dar Al-Farabi for this amazing copy, paper quality, and translation.</span>
