    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_872563496" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/872563496" />
    <a title="Tam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20465079-tam"><img alt="Tam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1399164430p2/20465079.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/872563496?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tam" href="/user/show/20465079-tam">Tam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20465079-tam?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20465079-tam?shelf=non-fic">non-fic</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer872563496" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9799216226278016813">Maalouf offers a precious account of the Crusades through the Muslim perspective. That contribution alone is enough to recommend this book. It is very accessible and directed towards general audience. However, I think a person having read the Crusades from a Western perspective would benefit much more since they could make useful comparisons, and they would not be too overwhelmed by names, dates, events, cities.<br/><br/>Some notable things to learn from this book is:<br/>- The inner struggles inside the Musli</span>
  <span id="freeText9799216226278016813" style="display:none">Maalouf offers a precious account of the Crusades through the Muslim perspective. That contribution alone is enough to recommend this book. It is very accessible and directed towards general audience. However, I think a person having read the Crusades from a Western perspective would benefit much more since they could make useful comparisons, and they would not be too overwhelmed by names, dates, events, cities.<br /><br />Some notable things to learn from this book is:<br />- The inner struggles inside the Muslim world: Arabs vs. Seljuk Turks, Sunni vs. Shia, many practical and strategic alliances among Muslims, between Muslims and Franjs (crusaders), between Muslims and Rums (Greeks/Byzantine)<br />- The significance of each event changes. Battle of Harran, for instance, plays a tremendous role in the Muslim account, but mentioned so briefly from the Western perspective. In other words, the flow of history, the ups and downs, differs, which is quite understandable but nevertheless eyeopening for people who are so long used to Westerners' making of history.<br /><br />Yet there are also problems, though they are not manifested so clearly if one does not read carefully enough. The problems become more obvious once readers arrive at the Epilogue. In this section, Maalouf tries to explain why Muslim succeeded in driving the Europeans out of Eastern Mediterranean yet eventually it is Europeans who are the winner in the modern world. Maalouf, in effect, assumes a huge point: <i>The crusades have left impacts on the Muslim world that can still be felt now</i>. This is strongly questionable. History is appropriated all the time in service of the present. But I do seriously question the direct consequences of the abysmal efforts of crusaders in the 11-13th century on the Muslim world. <br /><br />Crusaders never occupied a significant land in the Eastern Mediterranean. Its holding was tenuous at best, only a thin tiny coastal area. It never reached Baghdad, the center of Muslim world. It never captured Damascus fully even. Saying that "there can be no doubt that the schism between these two worlds dates from the Crusades, deeply felt by the Arabs, even today, as an act of rape" requires a much more careful examination that Maalouf did not have strong evidence for. <br /><br />Maalouf complains that Muslims at the time of the crusades failed to learn from European's achievements, namely the "stable" structure of succession in the Latin Kingdom. On the other hand, Europeans benefited so much from being open-minded to Muslim's civilization. Oops! First of all, throughout the book, Maalouf wasn't able to study the Latin Kingdom's process of succession very carefully. It is doubtful that such process is that peaceful. The very account of the two Islamo-Frankish alliances opposing each other in 1108 is quite an example of the problems in the structure of the crusader state. Furthermore, Arab culture at the time was much more sophisticated and developed, compared to the "barbarians" of the Western Europe. Would it not be understandable that Westerners so fascinated by the achievements of the Oriential civilization that they simply had to learn from the other, while for the Muslim, would it not be totally fine being scornful of those barbarians? <br /><br />Far and few between, Maalouf also interpreted the Crusade as an attempt of "colonization." This is problematic in many ways, since colonization first of all implies permanent settlement, which was never successful for the Crusaders. The kingdom was sustained only by waves of temporary pilgrims. And, if colonization was truly one goal, did they succeed at all? They did not have significant land. They did establish trade, but were Europeans able to "assimilate" the indigenous people into the Western culture? The short answer is no. On the contrary, many Europeans were assimilated into the rich Muslim world.<br /><br />And so, be very careful reading this account.<br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9799216226278016813" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


