  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_197384284" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/197384284" />
    <a title="Bethany" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5855599-bethany"><img alt="Bethany" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507421639p2/5855599.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/197384284?book_show_action=true">Aug 11, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bethany" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bethany" href="/user/show/5855599-bethany">Bethany</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780805208986" href="/book/show/64533.The_Crusades_Through_Arab_Eyes">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5855599-bethany?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer197384284" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2865337918180184332">On the front cover of the book there is a quotation from <i>The New Yorker</i> that says the book is &quot;A readable and entertaining mirror image of events that are as familiar in the West as fairy tales.&quot; This statement is a pithy, but generally accurate summation of what a reader will actually find in reading this book.<br/><br/>For one thing, anyone who knows anything about fairy tales in the West can tell you that absolutely no one agrees on the details for any of them. Was Cinderella&apos;s slipper fur or glass? Di</span>
  <span id="freeText2865337918180184332" style="display:none">On the front cover of the book there is a quotation from <i>The New Yorker</i> that says the book is "A readable and entertaining mirror image of events that are as familiar in the West as fairy tales." This statement is a pithy, but generally accurate summation of what a reader will actually find in reading this book.<br /><br />For one thing, anyone who knows anything about fairy tales in the West can tell you that absolutely no one agrees on the details for any of them. Was Cinderella's slipper fur or glass? Did her step-sisters cut off parts of their feet or did they accept that their feet weren't the correct fit and bid their erstwhile servant girl an embittered farewell? Or did the birds come and peck their eyes out for no discernible reason except that they were the villains and villains must come to excruciatingly bad ends?<br /><br />The story of the Crusades is much the same. From the Western standpoint, it was a (series of) noble war(s) to reclaim the Holy Land from heretic infidels (remember that if you weren't just the Pope's brand of Catholic you were a heretic by default, even if you didn't consider yourself Christian at all). The Muslim people who had lived in the area for time immemorial viewed them as an unprovoked series of invasions from Frankish barbarians who knew nothing of manners, culture, medicine, or even basic arithmetic.<br /><br />Maalouf cites many first-hand sources which range from dry to entertaining (Usama ibn Munqidh being an excellent example of the latter) and are well-chosen to highlight the points he wishes to make. The writing in between is informative and a careful reader will even observe that there is actual historical support for the <s>Orlando Bloom</s> Liam Neeson Crusade film <i>Kingdom of Heaven</i> as well as one of the clearest descriptions of the various Muslim rulers between 1096 and 1291 (Christian calendar), whose unfamiliar names can easily confuse a reader who is not already well-versed in the subject.<br /><br />In tone as well as content it very much resembles the sort of book one would read in conjunction with a college course which covers the Crusades, or perhaps provide background material for a course on Islamic studies. Since the book is written with the goal of accessibility, that clarity is an admirable feat, however the text itself is still a dry read for those not accustomed to reading historical texts, often going into detail that would seem unnecessary to such a reader and focusing on too many characters. To a medieval scholar the text is very readable compared to many others on the subject, and the relatively wide scope makes it an excellent jumping-off point for someone seeking people or events to study in greater depth.<br /><br />In summation, I must generally agree with <i>The New Yorker</i>: it was readable and the events chronicled therein are as open to interpretation as fairy tales, and as for the dryness of the text, I am given to wonder whether the blame for the text's dryness ought to be attributed to Maalouf or translator Jon Rothschild. Beggars can't be choosers, however, and since I do not speak or read Arabic beyond a very basic level I am grateful to have this text translated into English and available to me as a reader, though I would not recommend it to any of my non-history geek friends.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2865337918180184332" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

