<span id="freeTextContainer17052107455985875606">I liked this book primarily for its quotes from primary sources - Middle Eastern historians who mostly don&apos;t seem to have been translated to English (yet). I made a list of names:<br/><br/>* Ibn Jubayr (1144-1217) trans. into french by geuthner<br/>* Ibn al -Qalanisi (1073-1160 Damascus <br/>* Ibn al-Athir (1160-1233) (wrote a giant 13-volume history)<br/>* history of Nahr al-Kalb (Philip Hiti)<br/>* Kamal al-Din Ibn al-Adim (1192-1262) Aleppo<br/>* <a href='https://secure.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/wiki/Usama_ibn_Munqidh' rel='nofollow noopener'>Usamah Ibn Munqidh</a> (1138-ish) (Especially awesome! Writer, diplomat, politician, </span>
  <span id="freeText17052107455985875606" style="display:none">I liked this book primarily for its quotes from primary sources - Middle Eastern historians who mostly don't seem to have been translated to English (yet). I made a list of names:<br /><br />* Ibn Jubayr (1144-1217) trans. into french by geuthner<br />* Ibn al -Qalanisi (1073-1160 Damascus <br />* Ibn al-Athir (1160-1233) (wrote a giant 13-volume history)<br />* history of Nahr al-Kalb (Philip Hiti)<br />* Kamal al-Din Ibn al-Adim (1192-1262) Aleppo<br />* <a href="https://secure.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/wiki/Usama_ibn_Munqidh" rel="nofollow noopener">Usamah Ibn Munqidh</a> (1138-ish) (Especially awesome! Writer, diplomat, politician, emir, who knew Nur al-Din, Saladin, Mu'in al-Din 'Unar, and King Fulk.)<br />* <a href="https://secure.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/wiki/Abu%27l-Fida" rel="nofollow noopener">Abu'l-Fida</a> (writing 1289-ish) Very interesting! a geographer and poet who saw the Franks driven out of Tripoli. <br /><br />I had mixed feelings about the book's conclusion and theories, lots of generalizations about the West being open to new ideas and the East not (but too open to letting horsey barbarians get into their elite classes.) <br /><br />Bits that I marked as good with bookmarks: <br /><br />* The bits about Zangi, pp. 134-139<br />* Drama between Nul al-Din, his uncle Shirkuh, the Franks meeting al-Adid, and everything about Saladin (Ṣalāḥ ad-Dīn Yūsuf)<br />* long quote from Ibn al-Athir on p. 190 recounting a conversation between Raymond and Prince Arnat before the battle of Hittin which is also described vividly with the geography<br />* that one guy they put into prison sewed into a camel skin. I couldn't stop wondering about this as a form of torture. Is it that it shrinks, that it itches/is incredibly filthy and you rot inside it? All of the above?<br />* The descriptions of al-Kamil liking <a href="https://secure.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/wiki/Frederick_II,_Holy_Roman_Emperor" rel="nofollow noopener">Frederick II</a> and how they are all "yay kindred spirits, BFF" (p. 226)<br /> </span>
