<div id="review_1053286127" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1053286127" />
    <a title="Ramza" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15071953-ramza"><img alt="Ramza" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1428695093p2/15071953.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1053286127?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ramza" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ramza" href="/user/show/15071953-ramza">Ramza</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780805208986" href="/book/show/64533.The_Crusades_Through_Arab_Eyes">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15071953-ramza?shelf=to-re-read">to-re-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1053286127" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2929283247439087118">Phew, this read dragged on! Not that it was dull—the subject matter, in fact, is of great appeal to me—but I felt forced to put it aside repeatedly in favour of more enthralling fictional narratives, only to go back pages and refresh my memory whenever I picked it up after a long pause. <br/><br/>The writing is not entirely typical of most heavy historical accounts, but rather more fluently flowing in its chronicling. The frequent shifting back and forth between recounting the overall events and providing</span>
  <span id="freeText2929283247439087118" style="display:none">Phew, this read dragged on! Not that it was dull—the subject matter, in fact, is of great appeal to me—but I felt forced to put it aside repeatedly in favour of more enthralling fictional narratives, only to go back pages and refresh my memory whenever I picked it up after a long pause. <br /><br />The writing is not entirely typical of most heavy historical accounts, but rather more fluently flowing in its chronicling. The frequent shifting back and forth between recounting the overall events and providing insight into the private personae of the major players hinders a little with what might otherwise have been a seamless narrative, but it all in all remains a pleasant read, with scant details. <br /><br />I have yet to read a Western account of these very events before I could truly be in a position to judge on this book's objectivity, but Maalouf seems to provide a fairly unbiased one (except, of course, in what concerns the incorporated passages of ancient records from Arab historians who witnessed the Crusades). The inner struggles of the Muslim world at those times are very well documented and there is no attempt at hiding the sheer ineptitude of most its leaders. The author does a great job of immersing you into the conflict and imparting the pressure of the stakes at play. The sparse Franj perspective is unfortunate, but bearing in mind the book's title, it is to be expected. <br /><br />As much undemanding and accessible as this book endeavours to be, it is still likely to occasionally overwhelm and confuse with its many historical personalities and events. Considering my shamefully chaotic approach of this work, it definitely warrants a re-read on my part. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2929283247439087118" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


