    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1070433468" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1070433468" />
    <a title="Ed Callahan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16704962-ed-callahan"><img alt="Ed Callahan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1358894288p2/16704962.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1070433468?book_show_action=true">Jun 23, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ed Callahan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ed Callahan" href="/user/show/16704962-ed-callahan">Ed Callahan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780805208986" href="/book/show/64533.The_Crusades_Through_Arab_Eyes">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">historians, students, teacherss</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16704962-ed-callahan?shelf=theory-of-knowledge">theory-of-knowledge</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16704962-ed-callahan?shelf=world-history">world-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16704962-ed-callahan?shelf=european-history">european-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16704962-ed-callahan?shelf=military-history">military-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1070433468" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17502975382111739793">In Western Civilization it&apos;s easy to approach the Crusades from the perspective of &quot;well-intentioned failures,&quot; military endeavors to &quot;liberate the Holy Lands&quot; from Muslim control. The usual and convenient caricatures and stereotypes about both the Crusaders and the Muslim populations thus are easily confirmed, and we never quite learn how the other side saw things. In this regard, Maalouf&apos;s book, albeit dated, is a helpful corrective. <br/><br/>Early on in this concise history, he demonstrates that the &quot;</span>
  <span id="freeText17502975382111739793" style="display:none">In Western Civilization it's easy to approach the Crusades from the perspective of "well-intentioned failures," military endeavors to "liberate the Holy Lands" from Muslim control. The usual and convenient caricatures and stereotypes about both the Crusaders and the Muslim populations thus are easily confirmed, and we never quite learn how the other side saw things. In this regard, Maalouf's book, albeit dated, is a helpful corrective. <br /><br />Early on in this concise history, he demonstrates that the "situation on the ground" in the Middle East was hardly black and white. Then again, when it comes to history, is anything? Often forgotten in histories of the Crusades told from a Eurocentric perspective is the the acknowledgment of indigenous Christian populations who were more likely to side with Muslim leadership against the Crusaders, who were often referred to as the "Franj." This raises all sorts of questions about the nature and pervasive influence of cultural imperialism: new arrivals from Western Europe were just as likely to exhibit hostility to Christian communities which were parts of the Eastern and Oriental Orthodox traditions as they were toward adherents of Islam; and as Maalouf points out, to what extent did the indigenous Arab population really make political decisions about dealing with the Franj, since most of the effective power was held by individuals who were Turks, Armenians, and Kurds, not Arabs. Once the Crusader states were established, the internal politics of the Muslim world often resulted in creative and interesting alliances which more than a few times found Muslims and Christians allying against other Muslims. Identities being what they were, alliances were hardly monolithic, and Maalouf points to a recurrent political instability among the various Muslim hegemons which made it painfully difficult to present a united or even determined front against the Crusaders.<br /><br />Maalouf gives us excerpts from a number of Muslim historians, but shows a particular affinity for Ibn al-Athir, whose history of this time period is, even by Muslim accounts, voluminous. We also learn more about other leaders of note: Nur al-Din and Saladin in particular. I wish that Maalouf had spent more time considering the impact of the Muslim invasions on the destruction of the Abbasid Caliphate, but his real focus is on the relationship between the Franj and the Muslim world.<br /><br />While we may easily dismiss the Crusades as ancient history, Maalouf strongly argues that it continues to impact Middle Eastern self-perception, perhaps even to the point of creating a kind of insularity, inferiority complex, and discomfort with modern Middle Eastern interactions with the Western World. Perhaps. It would explain some of more radical reactions and puritanical streaks among groups such as Boko Haram, al-Qaeda, and the Taliban, all of whom play a kind of pick-and-choose game when it comes to appropriating or rejecting components of Western civilization and technology. But then again, this sort of a al carte approach marks the ancient and on-going dynamic of cultural diffusion.<br /><br />If Maalouf were to update the book it would be interesting to learn what has changed in his perspective. A lot of history has transpired between 1984, when the book was first copyrighted, and 2017. Would he, for example, agree with Osama Bin Laden's contention that Western military presence in the Middle East is a return to the Crusades? Where would he situate the more radical forms of jihad which have surfaced since at least the 1980s? But then again, this implies that a sustained strong comparison between the Crusades and the modern era can be made, or is valuable. That determination needs to be left to another generation.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17502975382111739793" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

